ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-1 The pilot departed Lee's Summit, Missouri, on the morning of the accident to visit family members in Kremmling, Colorado. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-2 He initiated flight following services with Denver Air Route Traffic Control Center (ARTCC) and then Denver TRACON while en route and at 1015:31, services were terminated. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-3 The pilot was advised to re-contact Denver ARTCC for further advisories, but failed to do so. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-4 The last National Track Analysis Program (NTAP) radar 'hit' of the accident airplane was at 1019:23 at an altitude of 12,600 feet. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-5 According to witnesses working several miles east of the accident site, they heard an airplane flying overhead traveling east to west and low to the ground; however, low cloud cover, snow and poor visibility prevented them from viewing the aircraft. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-6 A squall line 3 miles wide running north/south was passing through the area, with hail and cloud to cloud lightening. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-7 The mountains to the west and the direction in which the airplane was traveling were obscured. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-8 At 1943, an alert notice (ALNOT) was issued. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-9 A search was initiated, and the aircraft was located at 1430 the following afternoon. 
ntsb3671txt-1-5-5-0-10 The airplane was found along a 45 degree inclining slope at an elevation of 12,808 feet mean sea level on a glacier along the north face of Arapaho Peak on the east side of the Continental Divide. 
